Forensics Evidence Collection > [[Topic 4: Mounting Forensic Images: Analysis Tools & Techniques]]

After acquiring forensic images, you need to open them later to investigate the incident. The term mounting refers to the acquired image (i.e., the obtained evidence) being placed in a usable state for the analyst to access. Remember the last time you connected your USB drive to your computer? That's a typical mounting exercise; the USB drive has been assigned a drive letter, and drive data becomes accessible to you. A mounted forensic image is seen as a drive attached to the host system.

 

Once you mount the image, you can perform multiple things like scanning it with an AntiVirus, copying files out, examining different logs and analyzing artifacts...etc.

 

One popular tool to mount different image types is "Arsenal Image Mounter." It has excellent features, such as mounting in different modes. One of them, the Write temporary mode, a very helpful during investigations. It allows analysts to do work conveniently without fearing changing data on the original evidence.  It can revert any changes made to the image, intentionally and unintentionally. Think of it as creating an intact snapshot of the image at the beginning that you can revert to after you finish your analysis.

 

Arsenal Image Mounter write temporary option.

 

In addition, It can mount a wide range of image types such as Raw (dd), Advanced Forensics Format 4 (AFF4), EnCase (E01 and Ex01 and Virtual Machine Disk Files (VHD, VDI, XVA, VMDK, OVA).

 

Arsenal Image Mounter supported image types.

 

Aside from Arsenal Image Mounter, FTK Imager is another popular mounting tool offering similar features.

 

Note: When mounting a disk image, ensure that the image filesystem is supported by the OS you are mounting from; otherwise, you will need external utilities to browse the image. For example, mounting Linux (ext4) on Windows OS will not work because Windows does not support Linux ext filesystems.
